      "source": [
        "**Hints**:\n",
        "\n",
        "- Ask the user to enter the account number as an integer (use the `int()` function on top of the `input()` function) and store the input in a variable (let's say `acc_num`). \n",
        "\n",
        "- Check whether the account number entered by the user is present in the `cust_data` dictionary or not using the `not in` keyword. \n",
        "```\n",
        " while acc_num not in cust_data:\n",
        "    acc_num = int(input(\"Not found. Please enter your correct account\n",
        "                        number:\\n\"))\n",
        "\n",
        " ```\n",
        "\n",
        " This `while` loop will prompt the user with the error message till the user enters an existing account number in the `cust_data` dictionary.\n",
        "\n",
        "- If the user enters a valid account number, the user should be able to see the following options:\n",
        "  \n",
        "  1. Check balance \n",
        "  \n",
        "  2. Withdraw  \n",
        "  \n",
        "  3. Deposit\n",
        "\n",
        "  Get the input from user (either `1`, `2` or `3`) and store it in the `user_choice` variable. Check whether the user has entered a valid choice and if not, print `'Invalid input'`. \n",
        "  ```\n",
        "  while user_choice not in ['1','2','3']:\n",
        "    print(\"\\nInvalid input!\")\n",
        "    print(\"Enter 1 to check your balance.\n",
        "          \\nEnter 2 to withdraw an amount.\n",
        "          \\nEnter 3 to deposit an amount.\")\n",
        "    user_choice = input()\n",
        "  \n",
        "  ```\n",
        "\n",
        "  This `while` loop will prompt the user with `'Invalid input!'` message till the user enters a valid option (`1`, `2` or `3`).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "- If the user enters `1` i.e. *Check balance* option, then display the available account balance from the `cust_data` dictionary using `cust_data[acc_num]['amount']`, where `acc_num` is the variable storing the account number entered by the user. \n",
        "\n",
        " Here, the account number acts as a key to the dictionary containing the amount.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Else if the user enters `2` i.e. *Withdraw* option, then perform the following steps:\n",
        "  \n",
        "  1. Get the amount to be withdrawn from the user as an integer and store it in a variable (let's say `amt`).\n",
        "  \n",
        "  2. Check whether user has entered an amount greater than the available balance using `if amt > cust_data[acc_num]['amount']:`\n",
        "\n",
        "  3. If the user enters a valid amount to withdraw then subtract the withdrawn amount from the users account and update the `cust_data` dictionary using\n",
        "\n",
        "   ```\n",
        "      new_amt = int(cust_data[acc_num]['amount']) - amt\n",
        "      cust_data[acc_num]['amount'] = new_amt\n",
        "   ```\n",
        "- Else if the user enters `4` i.e. *Deposit* option, then perform the following steps:  \n",
        "\n",
        "   1. Get the amount to be deposited from the user as an integer and store it in a variable (let's say `amt`).\n",
        "\n",
        "  2. Add the amount to the users account and update the `cust_data` dictionary using\n",
        "\n",
        "   ```\n",
        "      new_amt = int(cust_data[acc_num]['amount']) + amt\n",
        "      cust_data[acc_num]['amount'] = new_amt\n",
        "   ```"
      ]
    },
